SOUTH African Airways Board has accepted the resignation its CEO Vuyani Jarana. Lack of accountability and trust, and depleting funds, are some of the reasons behind his resignation. After a daylong meeting, SAA board on Sunday night responded to Jarana’s resignation. “On behalf of the Board, I would like to thank Mr Jarana for his service and commitment to the airline. SAA chairman Bhekumuzi Magwaza said, “He contributed to returning confidence and credibility to the airline. We wish him well in his future endeavours,” According to the statement, since he joined SAA in November 2017, Mr Jarana has spearheaded the implementation of the long-term strategy to return the airline to financial and operational sustainability and position it to deliver effectively on its mandate. Magwaza said the airline will continue to implement actions to reduce SAA’s cost structure and make the airline more competitive domestically and globally. “In terms of his contractual obligations, Mr Jarana has committed to remain until the end of August to ensure an orderly transition of his responsibilities, which is a matter that the Board will consider. The Board of SAA will immediately commence the process of searching for a new Group CEO to take the strategy forward,” concluded Mr Magwaza.